[3] Cholera - Congo DR (Kinshasa)
Date: Thu 28 Dec 2017
Source: RFI [machine trans. edited]
http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20171228-rdc-une-nouvelle-epidemie-cholera-touche-kinshasa


In the DRC, health minister Oly Ilunga is deploring a new cholera outbreak in Kinshasa. Since 27 Nov 2017, 123 cases and 10 deaths have been reported, according to official figures. The health minister, however, argued that Kinshasa is not endemic for cholera and that everything is being done to contain the epidemic.

Cases of this cholera epidemic have been reported since 27 Nov 2017 in the Camp Luka district west of the city of Kinshasa. According to minister of health Oly Ilunga, these cases were imported from neighboring Kongo Central Province. "This man [the 1st recorded case in Kinshasa] stayed in Kimpese in Kongo Central [a Congo DR province formerly called Bas-Congo - Mod.LL] before going to Kinshasa. The alert was given immediately, and the provincial health division immediately took the lead to launch the response," he said.

Since January 2017, Kinshasa has experienced 444 cases and 38 deaths. According to the minister of health, this outbreak declared since November 2017 has no connection with previous cases of cholera reported in the capital. "The cases they had in early 2017 in April/May at Camp Kokolo were actually imported cases from the Equator," said Oly Ilunga.

According to the minister, the Kinshasa health system is equipped and ready to contain this epidemic. "This is not the 1st time that the province of Kinshasa is facing a cholera outbreak, and our teams in the provincial division are equipped to carry out the response against this disease," he said. Oly Ilunga also requested the involvement of the press to sensitize the public to respect basic hygiene measures.

